channel.title: RSC Map Generator
channel.description:
Hi. Once again, I made this for Project RSC but never used this for anything (it was supposed to be used on the website but meh). Anyway, it generates an image from original unedited rsc landscape, of the rsc map. It currently does not render bridges, nor multiple levels, therefore this project is incomplete.
You could do a few different things with this, such as dump each individual sector, or complete the map generator.
here is what this will render: [url=http://i.imgur.com/JdTqQ.png]http://i.imgur.com/JdTqQ.png[/url]
[url=http://uppit.com/zedvsm7yfj9u/RSC_Map_Generator.zip]RSC Map Generator[/url]
Edit: It's actually quite interesting to see the map unedited in a large picture like that. You can really see how jagex's landscape editor... sucked. lol, you can tell where each sector begin and ends, especially in al kharad. There is also a bit of repetitiveness in some areas.

item.description:
@CodeForFame wrote:

[quote=“imthenull, post:45, topic:469913”][quote author=CodeForFame link=topic=587233.msg4199656#msg4199656 date=1358003147]

yea it actually does that, but doesn’t actually write the image, my goal when making this was to dump one huge image of all the levels. i just couldn’t get the 'level’s positioned correctly with math, as i dont want to use absolute placement.[/quote]It seems like the entries in the cache aren’t being found, except for levels 0 and 3.

In the landscape I dumped, it has just as many entries as land.jag (minus 1), but doesn’t have any data for levels other than 3 or 0.

Also, it seems to find 120 entries in land.jag but 173 in maps.jag. In addition, it’s only writing 119 into the image.

Any ideas?

Unfortunately, no I have no idea. lol

Maybe where it loops through all the sectors you’re singling out the 0 and 3rd layer? idk[/quote]I figured it out by looking at the client. The difference was if it didn’t find it in the landscape.jag, it set the ground elevation and texture to 0, and continued on as if nothing was missing. Your implementation just skipped to the next one if nothing was found.
